Concept.text:
Vampires{newline}If you wish to start the game as a Vampire, you must choose the ‘Vampire Nobility’ option during character creation, this should be your final choice before loading into the campaign map. It will allow to choose your Blood Line. You either become a Vampire Noble or start your adventure as a Blood Knight. {newline}
{newline}Being a Vampire provides a unique set of bonuses and abilities, from the very start of your playthrough: You gain the ability to raise the dead, you can move faster at night and you are more agile than humans.
{newline}Note that you also will be facing some disadvantages, for example slower travel speed during the day. As a Vampire you will start your playthrough hated by the Empire and most other living factions.{newline}
{newline}Necromancers
{newline}If you wish to start the game as a necromancer, you must choose the Novice Necromancer option during character creation - this should be one of the final options given to you. Once selected you will load into the map with access to Necromancy magic and the ability to raise the dead after battles to supplement your army.{newline}
{newline}Wizards and Magic Users
{newline}To start the game as a wizard, and this applies to most factions, you must select the correct final option during character creation, which will contain ‘allows for the use of magic’ in the description.{newline}
{newline}For example within the Empire, choose to be a College Acolyte upon game start and you will load into the game with access to magic. Once loaded into the campaign map a prompt will let you choose the lore of magic you wish to specialise in. From this point onward you are free to play the campaign as normal with access to a number of starting spells. Remember you CANNOT learn more than one lore of magic as a human (unless you are a Damsel, see {TOR_CAREERS}).{newline}
{newline}Priests and Damsels of the Lady
{newline}Priest careers can be selected upon starting the game. They provide powerful battle prayers (see {TOR_PRAYERS}). 
{newline}
{newline}Knights Errant
{newline}The Knight of Bretonnia is one of the unique {TOR_CAREERS} you can start with when playing as Bretonnia.{newline}
{newline}Standard options
{newline}Choosing any other career start for your campaign will result in a similar experience as vanilla Bannerlord - you will load into the game with gear based on your choice and the freedom to make your own story from scratch. When no career is chosen at the beginning, you will instead start with the Mercenary career which provides various bonuses (see {TOR_CAREERS}).{newline}
{newline}
{newline}

Careers are a system you can engage with for both roleplaying and character development, providing unique skills and bonuses depending on your specialization. These Careers are similar to skill trees that require specific feats to be achieved to allow progression, which can include additional health points, increased damage, or party buffs related to the career in question.{newline}
  {newline}Skill Points, which are used to advance through a Career, are acquired by leveling up with the base Bannerlord system. For every level your character gains one Career point.{newline}
  {newline}Within a playthrough you are supposed to specialise in a single career choice; however there will be an option to change between careers but not without penalties, such as losing all your progress and abilities earned. You will have your skill points returned to you so that you can advance in your new career choice.{newline}
  {newline}Note: Switching careers may of course result in the loss of magic, prayers or abilities that can reduce your overall battle strength. In the current state switching is only possible by receiving a {TOR_BLOODKISS} as Mercenary.{newline}
  {newline}The current Career skill trees in the mod include Grail Knight, Blood Knight, Warrior Priest, Mercenary, Vampire Nobility and the Damsel. Each accompanied with their own unique and appropriately themed progression via their unique Career Skill tree found on the Character screen, in the upper right corner.{newline}
  {newline}Every career is divided into 3 ranks, each allowing you to pick special perks. The benefits of these perks vary from simple passive buffs to more advanced and unique benefits for the specific career.{newline}
  {newline}Career Abilities
  {newline}Some careers have a specific career ability. Career abilities allow for unique temporary combat buffs or unique action skills like turning into mist as a Vampire.{newline}
  {newline}
  {newline}
  Base Career: 
  {newline}
  {newline}
  Mercenary{newline}
  - Melee and ranged combat bonuses{newline}
  - Can earn extra gold from certain enemies and contracts{newline}
