   {newline}

Companions within our mod have been changed to better suit our setting; however, at this time the recruitment and interaction with these companion NPCs remain primarily unchanged. They are found in taverns and recruited with a single payment, just like vanilla Bannerlord.{newline}
  {newline}Similarily to the vanilla experience, these companions are generic and differ in equipment, but can specialize in custom skills and special abilities such as access to magic or prayers, which only the relevant companion type will have.{newline}
  {newline}The one notable difference are faction-specific companions, such as Vampires, which can be found solely in their appropriate territory. For example Vampire companions being found in Sylvanian taverns and Warrior Priests within the Empire.{newline}
  {newline}The companion types include Warrior Priests, Knights, Wizards, Vampires and more.{newline}

As a Vampire or necromancer, you can interact with certain cursed locations on the campaign map. These will allow you to summon undead units but the ritual can only be performed once a day. Cursed locations can be found within but are not limited to the swamps of Sylvania or Mousillon. This blighted land will cause attrition (damage to troops and characters) to the travelling party and healing won’t be possible until the area has been left. Over time these negative effects will grow stronger.{newline}
  {newline}As a non-Vampire or necromancer character, you can interact with these locations in a different way by conducting a warding ritual. This ritual will temporarily stop the recruitment of undead units by undead factions and remove the negative penalties for the player and any non-undead factions. To perform this ritual your party must have at lest 9 units and some will take damage during the process.{newline}
  {newline}

We have implemented our own damage system, which takes into account a variety of factors during battles - unit types and the damage or resistance modifiers being used by individual characters. The damage system works within the base Bannerlord physics-based damage system. A mighty well-timed blow will be further enhanced by magical and other non-physical effects. On the other hand units with physical resistance, like ethereal units, take less damage from non-magic weapons.{newline}
  {newline}Damage types{newline}
  - Physical: regular damage dealt from the vast majority of weapons and some spells. {newline}
  - Magical: some artifact weapons and most spells deal magical damage. {newline}
  - Fire: dealt by special guns and most Bright magic spells. {newline}
  - Holy: dealt by most prayers or even certain holy weapons.{newline}
  - Lightning: Heavens wizards and higher level Damsels make use of this damage type.{newline}
	{newline}Damage proportions
{newline}If a certain weapon or unit type possesses non-physical damage effects, their damage can be split into categories. For example spells deal full damage, aligned to the element of the magic in use.{newline}
	{newline}Buffs, debuffs and resistances
	{newline}Certain magical gear or abilities can enhance damage dealt, reduce damage taken or enhance a particular damage type. In a playthrough you may be able to, for example, both enhance the use of Bright magic while also reduce damage taken from Dark magic. It is important to note resistances and damage buffs must match the damage type they are blocking or enhancing.{newline}
	{newline}Attack types
	{newline}Certain buffs and spells are only beneficial to certain attack types, which can include spell damage, melee damage or ranged damage. Only the benefits that match their attack type will be considered for the hit. {newline}
    {newline}Wardsave
	{newline}A special form of resistance is Wardsave. Wardsave acts last on the damage calculation, reducing the overall damage by a certain percentage. {newline}
	{newline}Damage calculation
	{newline}For a more detailed explanation of the damage calculation please head over to our Discord channel.{newline}
	 {newline}
	 {newline}

One of the major features of our mod is the use of artillery in battles. This is tied to the Engineering skill of players. Levelling your Engineering skill will allow you to acquire and use artillery on the battlefield. Once the player reaches 50 Engineering, they will able to purchase artillery from certain factions. Every 50 levels of Engineering allow the player to field an additional piece of artillery, up to maximum 6.{newline}
  {newline}The location or means of acquiring {TOR_ARTILLERY} will differ between each faction.{newline}
  {newline}

Cannons and Mortars
  {newline}The player can acquire Great Cannons and Mortars from the Imperial city of Nuln, after speaking to the Master Engineer NPC found in the city. Cannons and Mortars are only available to Imperial characters and have a number of requirements: to access the purchase screen alone a quest must first be completed, given by the Master Engineer.
  {newline}To buy and use Imperial artillery the player must have at least 50 Engineering, be part of an Imperial faction and have artillery crew in their party. Every additional 50 levels of Engineering allow the player to field an additional artillery piece.{newline}
  {newline}Field Trebuchets
  {newline}The player can acquire Field Trebuchets in Bretonnian towns with Wood Workshops by interacting with the trader.
  {newline}This powerful piece of artillery requires the player to have at least 50 Engineering. To properly operate Trebuchets infantry units need to be assigned to a placed artillery piece during the battle. Every additional 50 levels of Engineering allow the player to field an additional Trebuchet.{newline}
  {newline}
  {newline}

One of our {TOR_ATTRIBUTES}, Gunpowder, is of course tied to the use of weapons like handguns. The player must use handguns or other blackpowder weapons in battles to level up their Gunpowder skill. Purchasing these weapons can be done by creating an Imperial character, hitting level 50 in Engineering and completing the quest given by the Master Engineer in Nuln. You can also buy them from traders in various cities.{newline}
  {newline}Finding and looting lower-quality guns or reading a Skill Book on Gunpowder is an excellent way to start this process early.
  {newline}

Magic and Necromancy share many similar features - they can both be accessed by selecting relevant choices in the character creation or accessed by a non-magical character during a playthrough.{newline}
  {newline}
  To do this, the player must speak to a Magister/Dark Magister NPC and request a ‘magic test’, which will essentially ‘test’ the player's aptitude for the Winds of Magic and allow you to make use of magic from then onwards.{newline}
  {newline}
  Magic and Necromancy have tiers and progressions. To grow stronger and access stronger spells you must use magic in battles and then speak to the Magister NPC relevant to your faction: for Necromancers or Dark magic users that would be the Dark Magister whereas for Empire factions it would simply be Magister. They can be found in every Imperial or Sylvanian city.  
  {newline}
  Related Topics:{newline}
